modern C S S, support. Modular C S S three and, No C S S four: To avoid monolithic spec bottlenecks,

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.000
the C S S Working Group split C S S into modular specifications after C S S two one.

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.000
Each module, Selectors, Color, Flexbox, Grid, et ceteraadvances on its own, Level.

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.000
All modules at Level three were informally termed, C S S three, but there was never a single C S S three spec.

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.000
The Working Group explicitly moved away from version numbers, there is no C S S four.

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.000
Instead, modules increment to Level four, Level five, et ceterawhen they add new features.

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.000
For example, Selectors Level three was followed by Selectors Level four, ongoing, but we don't call this, C S S four.

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.000
The current state of C S S is defined by C S S Snapshots, which collect the stable, interoperable specs at a point in time.

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.000
This modular approach has allowed C S S to evolve faster and more incrementally,

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.000
though it requires developers to track many spec modules.

